{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473042","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473042"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:03:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:03:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1809"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1809"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.2,0.27,0.03,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1809"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54060"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1809"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1809"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39533"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13778"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14238"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16298"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16388"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42408"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44060"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54060"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 10-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department of a tertiary referral hospital with a six-hour history of increasing upper abdominal pain. He was kicked in the abdomen during a soccer game earlier in the day but continued playing. The pain only started at the end of the match. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft and not distended, but there is an area of tenderness in the left upper quadrant. An intravenous line is inserted, a saline infusion started, and a CT scan performed to assess for an underlying injury (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Splenic artery embolisation","Laparotomy and splenectomy","Continued observation","Paracentesis","Laparotomy and splenorrhaphy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a 10-year-old boy with a Grade III splenic injury following blunt abdominal trauma. The CT scan shows a ruptured parenchymal haematoma and blood within the peritoneal cavity, consistent with this diagnosis. The patient is haemodynamically stable, which is a crucial factor in determining the management approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinued observation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management plan in this scenario. Non-operative management is the preferred approach for splenic injuries in children, especially when they are haemodynamically stable. This approach is recommended for all stable children, regardless of the injury grade. In well-equipped urban hospitals, this strategy has a success rate of up to 95% for splenic preservation. The patient should be closely monitored, with intervention only considered if there is deterioration in his condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESplenic artery embolisation\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered in adult patients if there was a visible blush on the arterial phase of the CT scan. However, paediatric patients rarely require angiography or angioembolisation for splenic injuries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparotomy and splenectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would be overly aggressive in this case. Surgical intervention is typically reserved for haemodynamically unstable patients, which is not the situation described here. Preserving the spleen is particularly important in children due to the risk of overwhelming post-splenectomy infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacentesis\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this scenario. It would not address the underlying splenic injury and could potentially worsen the situation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparotomy and splenorrhaphy\u003C/strong\u003E (surgical repair of the spleen) is also too aggressive for this stable patient. While spleen-preserving surgery might be considered in some cases, non-operative management is preferred when possible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principles in managing paediatric splenic trauma include recognising the importance of splenic preservation, utilising appropriate imaging (CT scan is the modality of choice), and opting for non-operative management in stable patients. This approach has revolutionised the treatment of paediatric splenic injuries, leading to better outcomes and reduced complications compared to routine surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Non-operative management is the preferred approach for splenic injuries in haemodynamically stable children, regardless of injury grade.","CT scan is the imaging modality of choice for assessing splenic injuries in children.","Splenic preservation is crucial in children due to the risk of overwhelming post-splenectomy infection."],"references":["Coccolini F, Montori G, Catena F, et al. Splenic trauma: WSES classification and guidelines for adult and pediatric patients. World J Emerg Surg. 2017; 12:40. DOI 10.1186/s13017-017-0151-4","Gill S, Hoff J, Mila A, et al. Post-traumatic Splenic Injury Outcomes for Nonoperative\nand Operative Management: A Systematic Review. World J Surg 2021; 45:2027\u201336"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39533"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1809"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18460"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18460"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cbe4d928-7851-4e19-9bea-b0ecabd932ef.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cbe4d928-7851-4e19-9bea-b0ecabd932ef.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":270,"height":209}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39533","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39533"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-29T11:18:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-29T11:20:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1809"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54060"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Manage